# Public app components and UI

The public app should feel polished, readable, and consistent with the existing Otaku Corner visual language. Preserve the current component patterns, responsive behavior, and domain-focused composition.

## Client components

- Use `"use client"` only when a file actually needs client behavior:
  - React state or effects
  - TanStack client hooks
  - browser APIs
  - media queries
  - dialogs or interactive UI
  - animation hooks
  - intersection observer hooks
- Keep route files server-first unless they must be client components.
- Keep client hooks in `src/hooks`.
- Keep large procedural UI logic out of components when a hook can own the behavior.

## Component exports

- Use one primary React component per component file.
- Prefer default function exports for primary components:

```tsx
export default function MediaListHeader(props: MediaListHeaderProps) {
  // ...
}
```

- Use named exports for helper builders and config values when they are imported by multiple files.
- Keep file-private prop types and helper types unexported unless another file imports them.
- When grouping siblings without extra DOM, use `<Fragment>...</Fragment>` with `import { Fragment } from "react"` rather than empty fragment shorthand `<>...</>`.

## Media list component pattern

- Media list pages should be built from:
  - media-specific list config
  - `MediaListProvider`
  - `MediaListHeader`
  - `MediaListSection`
  - shared hooks such as `useMediaListHeader` and `useMediaListBody`
- Do not fork separate full list implementations for anime, manga, and light novels.
- Put media-specific card rendering, filters, labels, empty/loading copy, and entity lookups in the media-specific config files:
  - `AnimeListConfig.tsx`
  - `MangaListConfig.tsx`
  - `LightNovelListConfig.tsx`
- Keep the shared media list components generic and driven by config.
- Maintain infinite loading through a sentinel element and `react-intersection-observer`, not ad-hoc scroll listeners.

## Media detail component pattern

- Shared detail page layout belongs in `MediaDetailPage`.
- Media-specific detail configuration belongs in:
  - `AnimeDetailConfig.tsx`
  - `MangaDetailConfig.tsx`
  - `LightNovelDetailConfig.tsx`
- Keep the top section, synopsis card, score card core, score breakdowns, review tabs, and spoiler modal reusable.
- Build review tabs with `buildMediaDetailReviewTab`.
- Use helpers from `@/lib/media-detail/media-detail-helpers` for score criteria, labels, score percentages, genre tags, and counts.
- Use `pickMediaImageSrc` from `@/lib/media-detail/media-images` for poster image selection.

## Home page pattern

- Keep homepage sections focused:
  - `HomeHeroWithNav`
  - `HomeYearProgressSection`
  - `HomeInsightsCarousel`
  - `HomeQuoteSection`
  - `GeneralFooter`
- Use `PUBLIC_MEDIA_TYPE_CONFIG` from `@/lib/media/public-media-type` for cross-media display labels, counts, chart keys, and link construction.
- Do not hard-code parallel anime/manga/light novel display metadata in each home component when it can come from the shared media config.

## UI primitives

- The `src/components/ui` directory contains shadcn-style primitives and small shared UI building blocks.
- Always prefer shadcn-style components and existing `src/components/ui` primitives for common UI needs.
- Installing a new shadcn component is allowed when the app does not already have a suitable primitive, but first search the existing `src/components/ui` directory and nearby feature components.
- Most UI needs should be satisfied by the existing primitives. Add new shadcn components sparingly and only when they fit the established design system.
- When adding a new shadcn component, keep it in `src/components/ui`, preserve the local import style, and adapt it to use `cn` from `@/lib/shared/utils`.
- Do not put feature-specific business logic into UI primitives.
- Keep UI primitive APIs general and composable.
- When changing a primitive, review all public app call sites because primitives are shared broadly.
- Import `cn` from `@/lib/shared/utils`.
- Prefer existing primitives (`Button`, `Badge`, `Card`, `Select`, `Tabs`, `Dialog`, `Popover`, etc.) over new one-off markup.
- Do not hand-roll common controls such as dialogs, dropdowns, popovers, selects, tabs, sheets, command menus, cards, badges, buttons, inputs, or separators when a shadcn primitive exists or can be installed cleanly.

## Icons and labels

- Use `lucide-react` icons where suitable.
- Icons that communicate meaning should have accessible labels through surrounding text, `aria-label`, or hidden text.
- Decorative icons should use `aria-hidden`.
- Buttons with only icons must have an accessible name.
- Keep public-facing copy consistent with the existing voice: concise, personal, and domain-specific.

## Motion and reduced motion

- The public app uses `framer-motion` for subtle entrance and highlight animation.
- Respect `useReducedMotion` in animated components.
- Do not add animation that changes layout dimensions after hydration.
- Avoid scroll listeners for reveal or load-more behavior when existing intersection-observer patterns work.
- Keep animation constants near the component that owns them unless reused across multiple components.

## Styling conventions

- Use Tailwind utility classes consistent with the existing public app style.
- Preserve the current soft white, rose, slate, violet, orange, and translucent/backdrop treatment unless a design task intentionally changes it.
- Avoid introducing unrelated design-system changes during feature work.
- Keep cards, panels, headers, badges, and filters visually consistent with the current media list and detail pages.
- Do not place text where it can overlap or overflow on mobile.
- Use stable dimensions for grids, media, controls, and sentinel areas to avoid layout shift.
- Use `container` and existing responsive layout conventions.

## Images

- Use `next/image` for public assets and remote media images.
- Use the configured image hosts in `next.config.ts`.
- Use `NEXT_PUBLIC_R2_HOSTNAME` for R2/Cloudflare-hosted images when configuring remote image loading.
- Keep decorative images `alt=""`.
- Use meaningful alt text for content images that are not decorative.
- Use `/no-poster.webp`, `/loading.webp`, `/no-result.webp`, and related public assets where the existing UI expects them.

## Accessibility

- Preserve keyboard-accessible controls.
- Do not replace buttons, selects, dialogs, tabs, or menus with non-semantic `div` click handlers.
- Dialogs need titles, even if visually hidden.
- Form controls need labels or accessible names.
- Status badges and loading states should be understandable from text, not color alone.

## Component size and extraction

- If a component grows hard to scan, extract focused subcomponents or hooks.
- Prefer config arrays and `.map()` for repeated UI sections.
- Avoid copying large JSX blocks for anime, manga, and light novel variants.
- Keep extracted components close to their feature folder unless they are truly shared across the app.
